physics

Class Beam

  • java.lang.Object
    • physics.Beam

  • public class Beam
extends Object
    Beams behave like springs, and calculate the forces impacted on Nodes based on the parameters and the distance between the two nodes.
    Author:
    janne

    • Constructor Detail

      • Beam

        public Beam(Node node1,
            Node node2,
            double materialStiffness,
            double mass,
            double strength)
        Constructs a Beam with the given parameters that is attached to the given Nodes. Sets the length of the beam to the distance between the Nodes.
        Parameters:
        node1 - A node to attach to the Beam.
        node2 - A node to attach to the Beam.
        materialStiffness - The stiffness of the Beam. This parameter gives the stiffness of the material, so a longer Beam with the same materialStiffness will stretch/compress more with the same force.
        mass - The mass of the Beam
        strength - The maximum force that the Beam can take before breaking.

      • Beam

        public Beam(Node node1,
            Node node2,
            double materialStiffness,
            double mass,
            double strength,
            double length)
        Constructs a Beam with the given parameters that is attached to the given Nodes.
        Parameters:
        node1 - A node to attach to the Beam.
        node2 - A node to attach to the Beam.
        materialStiffness - The stiffness of the Beam. This parameter gives the stiffness of the material, so a longer Beam with the same materialStiffness will stretch/compress more with the same force.
        mass - The mass of the Beam
        strength - The maximum force that the Beam can take before breaking.
        length - Sets the length of the Beam. If set to 0, the Beam will set the length to match the distance between the attached nodes.

    • Method Detail

      • calculateNewState

        public void calculateNewState()
        Calculates the new state of the Beam. This updates the force of the Beam, and if the force exceeds the Beam's strength, the Beam breaks and the force is set to zero. A broken Beam always has a force of zero.

      • getForceVector

        public Vector getForceVector(Node node)
        Returns the force that is applied to the given node.
        Parameters:
        node - One of the Nodes that is attached to the Beam.
        Returns:
        The Force vector that represents the force applied by this beam.
